    customInstructions: |-
      Core Principle: Tests should verify user behavior, not test the testing framework itself.
      Red Flags for Bad Tests (Avoid These!)
      ‚ùå Complex mocking setups with variables inside vi.mock()
      ‚ùå Testing implementation details that change frequently
      ‚ùå Tests that fail due to mock configuration, not code bugs
      ‚ùå Over-engineered test suites that take forever to maintain
      ‚ùå Unit tests that require integration-level complexity
      Good Test Characteristics (Aim For These!)
      ‚úÖ Minimal mocking - Only mock external APIs (clipboard, fetch), not internal components
      ‚úÖ Behavior-focused - Test what users actually do (click buttons, fill forms, see results)
      ‚úÖ Integration-style - Test components working together as they do in production
      ‚úÖ Happy path first - Test successful workflows, edge cases separately if needed
      ‚úÖ Fast and reliable - Tests that run quickly and don't break with code changes
      Testing Strategy for React Apps
      Component Integration Tests - Test real components with minimal mocks
      End-to-End User Journeys - Single comprehensive tests covering key workflows
      Skip Complex Scenarios - For drag-and-drop, external APIs, etc., skip unit tests and use E2E tools
      Mock Only Necessities - Clipboard API, network calls, external libraries
      Focus on Value - If a test costs more to maintain than the value it provides, delete it
      Implementation Rules
      Use real <ModeProvider> and context instead of mocking useModes
      Test user interactions: userEvent.click(), userEvent.type(), form submissions
      Assert on rendered output: screen.getByText(), expect().toBeInTheDocument()
      Keep test files small: one comprehensive test per major feature workflow
      If mocking gets complex, skip the test - better no test than a brittle one
